d 'the family' as a targeted recipient group without specifying further. One intervention ( $1.6 \\%$ ) targeted siblings. ${ }^{47}$ Interventions were delivered in-person ( $n=23 ; 37.7 \\%$ ), virtually ( $n=13 ; 21.3 \\%$ ) or using both modes ( $n=18 ; 29.5 \\%$ ). Seven interventions ( $11.5 \\%$ ) did not specify a delivery mode.\n\n## 3.5 | Family-centred care domains addressed by interventions and intervention components\n\nMost interventions ( $n=56 ; 91.8 \\%$ ) addressed more than one of the eight family-centred care domains that we considered, with nearly half ( $n=26,42.6 \\%$ ) addressing at least four domains (Appendix 58). The most common domains addressed by interventions were communication and information provision ( $n=45 ; 73.8 \\%$ ), family involvement ( $n=37 ; 60.7 \\%$ ) and access to care ( $n=30 ; 49.2 \\%$ ) (Figure 3). The least common domains addressed by interventions were physical comfort ( $n=7 ; 11.5 \\%$ ) and emotional support ( $n=18$; 29.5\\%) (Figure 3).\n\nTable 4 describes types of approaches taken to addressing each family-centred care domain, with intervention examples. For example, care coordination was most commonly addressed by adopting a team-based approach to care delivery, in which services are provided"
